      Apes vs. APEs
   =20
 =20

I have previously  expressed my fondness=C2=A0for AMC Entertainment Holding=
s Inc.=E2=80=99s APEs=C2=A0scheme. AMC was a big meme stock and had=C2=A0a =
lot of investors who wanted to buy its stock; it also needed a lot of money=
 and was happy to sell stock to them. But its corporate charter only allowe=
d it to issue about 524 million common shares, and AMC was running out of s=
tock to sell. It asked its shareholders to authorize more shares but =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0well, they didn=E2=80=99t exactly say no. What happened is that AM=
C withdrew the request for more shares because it couldn=E2=80=99t get enou=
gh votes, and it couldn=E2=80=99t get enough votes=C2=A0in part=C2=A0becaus=
e its existing shareholders were worried about dilution, but also in (proba=
bly larger) part because AMC=E2=80=99s overwhelmingly retail investor base =
simply doesn=E2=80=99t vote. Retail shareholders tend not to vote much on a=
nything; they are hard to reach, and voting your shares is confusing and po=
intless enough that ordinary retail investors rarely do it.
But AMC needed a majority of all of its shares to vote to authorize new sha=
res; not voting is equivalent to voting no. So AMC had people who wanted to=
 buy stock, it wanted to sell them stock, and it (probably) thought that it=
s shareholders wanted it to issue more stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it couldn=
=E2=80=99t reach those shareholders to get them to vote to approve more sto=
ck.
So AMC came up with a clever trick, the APEs, AMC Preferred Equity Units. I=
t created a new class of preferred stock; each preferred share has the econ=
omic rights of 100 shares of common stock, gets 100 votes and votes togethe=
r with the common stock on everything. Then it gave its shareholders 1/100t=
h of a preferred share =E2=80=94=C2=A0an APE =E2=80=94=C2=A0for each common=
 share, creating sort of a stock split. Then it started selling more APEs t=
o raise cash, and sold a big block of APEs to a hedge fund called Antara Ca=
pital. And now it is=C2=A0 asking its shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0APE holde=
rs and common shareholders, all voting together =E2=80=94=C2=A0to approve a=
 charter amendment to authorize new shares, do a reverse share split and co=
nvert the APEs into common shares. This vote should succeed, because:
=09There are now many more APEs than common shares, and the APE holders hav=
e an incentive to vote yes. (APEs trade at a big discount to common shares,=
 and if the APEs are converted that discount will naturally close.)=09APEs =
are more likely to be held by professional arbitrageurs, not retail investo=
rs, so they are more likely to vote.=09A big block of APEs is held by Antar=
a, which has signed an agreement to vote its shares in favor of the amendme=
nt.=09The preferred shares underlying the APEs are held by a depositary, Co=
mputershare Trust Co., which has agreed to vote=C2=A0all=C2=A0of the prefer=
red shares in proportion to how any voting APEs vote. So if 20% of the APEs=
 vote yes, 5% vote no, and 75% don=E2=80=99t vote at all, Computershare wil=
l vote 80% of the preferred stock for yes, which will be enough to pass the=
 amendments even if all of the common stock doesn=E2=80=99t vote (or votes =
no).

AMC=E2=80=99s problem was that its retail investors don=E2=80=99t vote, and=
 it came up with a solution. I like it!
Not everyone does. Before=C2=A0the APEs, it probably made sense for AMC=E2=
=80=99s common shareholders to vote to authorize more shares: AMC needed mo=
ney, and if it could sell shares at high prices to new investors, that was =
good for existing shareholders. (If you are selling stock at prices higher =
than fundamental value, that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0accretive, not dilutive.
  [1]
) A rational AMC shareholder, pre-APEs, probably should have wanted to auth=
orize more shares, even if the shareholders=C2=A0did not bother to=C2=A0vot=
e=C2=A0to make that happen.=C2=A0
But now that the APEs=C2=A0are=C2=A0outstanding, the common shareholders mi=
ght rationally not want to convert them into common stock. The APEs closed =
on Friday at $2.40 per APE; the common stock closed at $5.24. When the APEs=
 convert into common, those prices will converge. It=E2=80=99s not entirely=
 clear if the final price should be closer to $2.40 or $5.24, but it=E2=80=
=99s plausible that it would be somewhere in the middle, meaning that votin=
g for the conversion would reduce=C2=A0the value of the common stock. If yo=
u are a common shareholder, converting all the APEs into common stock defin=
itely=C2=A0is=C2=A0dilutive, and you might not like it.
  [2]
=C2=A0You might vote against authorizing new shares. That doesn=E2=80=99t m=
atter very much: The APEs have a majority of the voting power and are very =
incentivized to vote for their own conversion. But you might be mad.
You might sue.=C2=A0Here is a lawsuit against AMC that was filed in Delawar=
e Chancery Court yesterday:

This Action challenges a course of complex and disloyal corporate engineeri=
ng by the Defendants=E2=80=94described by AMC=E2=80=99s Chief Executive Off=
icer and Chairman, Defendant Adam M. Aron (=E2=80=9CAron=E2=80=9D) as an ex=
ercise in =E2=80=9C3-D chess=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94 devised to achieve a simple =
aim: eviscerating the voting power of AMC=E2=80=99s Class A stockholders in=
 order to force through approval of a proposed dilutive share count increas=
e that those stockholders repeatedly had rebuffed and were not willing to s=
upport at the corporate ballot box. ...
Seizing on increases in AMC=E2=80=99s stock price driven by retail investor=
s, AMC sold nearly all of the Company=E2=80=99s remaining authorized shares=
 of Class A common stock to raise capital. Thereafter, AMC proposed on mult=
iple occasions to amend the Company=E2=80=99s certificate of incorporation =
to authorize the issuance of additional shares of Class A common stock=E2=
=80=94but those proposals were rebuffed repeatedly by the Company=E2=80=99s=
 existing Class A common stockholders, who twice forced the withdrawal of s=
uch proposals.
In response, AMC embarked on a course of complex corporate engineering for =
the plain and obvious purpose of circumventing the will of the Company=E2=
=80=99s existing stockholders and securing a dilutive increase in the numbe=
r of authorized Class A shares over their unambiguous opposition. =E2=80=A6
With outstanding APEs outnumbering the Class A common shares by nearly 2 to=
 1 and the Depositary Voting Requirement supercharging the APEs=E2=80=99 vo=
ting power as a class vis-=C3=A0-vis AMC=E2=80=99s Class A stockholders, AM=
C is poised to finally force through the Class A share count increase that =
was opposed repeatedly by Class A stockholders before AMC and the Board too=
k steps to reconstitute their electorate.
AMC and the Board presumably believe their game of =E2=80=9C3-D chess=E2=80=
=9D against the Class A stockholders is approaching checkmate. But, as deta=
iled herein, the vote cannot be allowed to proceed as planned. In their zea=
l to circumvent the will of the Class A stockholders, Defendants have breac=
hed their fiduciary duties and violated the [Delaware General Corporation=
=C2=A0Law].

There are two main arguments. One is sort of a technical one: Delaware law =
says that the common shareholders have to get to vote on any charter amendm=
ent that would =E2=80=9Calter or change the powers, preferences, or special=
 rights of the shares of such class so as to affect them adversely,=E2=80=
=9D and the shareholders here argue that=C2=A0the issuance of the APEs=C2=
=A0reduced their rights and so should have been put to a shareholder vote.
  [3]
 The APEs are what is called =E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred stock,=E2=80=9D=
 meaning that AMC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0corporate charter=C2=A0allows the board of=
 directors to create and issue new preferred stock with whatever terms they=
 like, but the argument here is that creating the APEs reduced the rights o=
f the common and so separately violated the law:

At the time the Board created the Preferred Shares, AMC had only one class =
of authorized stock with voting rights, its Class A common stock. The right=
 to vote on matters requiring stockholder approval was not shared with any =
other class. Thus, the right to vote was a special characteristic of the co=
mmon stock in the capital structure of AMC.
Specifically, the sole or primary purpose of the Preferred Stock=E2=80=99s =
creation and issuance was to eviscerate the voting power of the Company=E2=
=80=99s Class A=C2=A0stockholders and effectively fashion a new electorate =
that, unlike the pre-existing stockholder base, would not rebuff the Board=
=E2=80=99s proposals to issue additional common stock. That is, before the =
creation of the Preferred Stock, AMC=E2=80=99s Class A stockholders had the=
 power and right to reject a specific proposal desired by the Board. This p=
ower and right conflicted with the desires of the Board, so the Board creat=
ed and issued the Preferred Stock for the purpose of removing that power an=
d right from the Company=E2=80=99s Class A stockholders.=C2=A0

I am not really convinced =E2=80=94=C2=A0if this is right, then that means =
that boards can never issue=C2=A0voting preferred stock without shareholder=
 approval, which might make sense but would come as=C2=A0a surprise =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but you can see the appeal of it. It=C2=A0is=C2=A0strange to think=
 that=C2=A0boards could issue new shares with unlimited voting power withou=
t shareholder approval.
The other argument is that the board violated its fiduciary duty to shareho=
lders: Even if the technical mechanics of the APEs all work, AMC created th=
e APEs to get around its shareholders=E2=80=99 preferences, which seems ick=
y and disloyal. From the complaint:
The Director Defendants approved the creation and sale of the Preferred Sto=
ck, imposed the Depositary Voting Requirement, and arranged for the impendi=
ng vote on the Proposals all for the purpose of circumventing the will of t=
he Company=E2=80=99s existing stockholders, who previously had rejected pro=
posals by the Board to increase the total number of authorized shares of Cl=
ass A common stock=E2=80=94essentially creating a new electorate=C2=A0and n=
ew voting rules, simply because they did not have the votes to get what the=
y wanted. All of these steps were taken for the very purpose of reversing t=
he likely outcome of Defendants=E2=80=99 desired vote to increase the autho=
rized number of Class A shares. This course of conduct constituted a breach=
 of fiduciary duty.
Here again I think I sympathize with the board. It=E2=80=99s their job to r=
un the company. In the exercise of their=C2=A0fiduciary duty, thinking abou=
t what is best for the company and its shareholders, they figured the compa=
ny would be better off issuing more stock. Their reasoning for that =E2=80=
=94 that the company=C2=A0needed money and=C2=A0people  wanted to buy the s=
tock at $60! =E2=80=94=C2=A0was, I think,=C2=A0impeccable.
  [4]
=C2=A0But they couldn=E2=80=99t do it, because they couldn=E2=80=99t get sh=
areholder approval, in part because shareholders disagreed with them but in=
 large part because the shareholders simply didn=E2=80=99t vote. The compan=
y had a problem, its shareholders could not get their act together to solve=
 it, so the board solved it for them. That=E2=80=99s what the board is supp=
osed to do, and Delaware courts do tend to be pretty sympathetic to boards =
of directors who make what they think is the right decision for their compa=
ny even if the shareholders don=E2=80=99t like it.=C2=A0
But they are less sympathetic to boards who try to take voting rights away =
from shareholders, and there is something about the APEs that feels like ch=
eating. So I don=E2=80=99t know what will happen. The special meeting to au=
thorize new shares and convert the APEs into common is  scheduled for March=
 14; the complaining shareholders=C2=A0have asked to postpone it for 60 day=
s while they argue to block it in court.
One other point here. Shareholder class action lawsuits like this are now u=
sually filed by institutional investors, often municipal retirement funds.
  [5]
=C2=A0The lead plaintiff here =E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholder who brought th=
e lawsuit =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the=C2=A0Allegheny County Employees=E2=80=99 Re=
tirement System, a pretty normal shareholder class-action plaintiff, yet on=
e who is somehow unrepresentative of AMC=E2=80=99s meme-stock shareholders.=
 Really you want a pseudonymous individual Reddit poster to lead the lawsui=
t.

