The rule in the US is roughly=C2=A0that if you are an institution =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0a pension fund, an endowment, an investment firm, a bank, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and you own more than $100 million worth of stocks, you have to di=
sclose your stock holdings every quarter.
  [7]
=C2=A0You file Form 13F with the US Securities and Exchange Commission, and=
 it is publicly available and everyone can see what stocks you own.
If you don=E2=80=99t like this, there are reasonably standard solutions. Th=
e rule is actually that you have to file Form 13F if you =E2=80=9Cexercise =
investment discretion=E2=80=9D over your stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning basi=
cally that you decide what stocks to buy and sell
  [8]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0so the trick is not to do that. If you have $1 billion=
 to invest in the stock market, you go to a big institutional investment ma=
nager and say =E2=80=9Chi, here=E2=80=99s $1 billion, please buy some stock=
s for me.=E2=80=9D You agree on some investment criteria =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 mandate for your investment =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you pay the manager some fe=
es, and the manager buys the stocks for you. This saves you all sorts of ag=
gravation =E2=80=94=C2=A0picking the stocks, doing the trading, setting up =
custody arrangements, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it also probably saves you fr=
om filing a Form 13F, if that=E2=80=99s your goal. Instead, the investment =
management firm files a Form 13F showing all of the stocks that it owns =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that it =E2=80=9Cexercises investment discretion=E2=80=9D over =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0for its various clients, including you. You are just an anon=
ymous client; your data is aggregated with the rest of the clients.
Presumably if you=E2=80=99re a big enough account, and interested enough in=
 the markets, you might end up doing some kibbitzing about what your invest=
ment manager is buying. The manager=E2=80=99s mandate for your account migh=
t be narrow and customized for=C2=A0your interests; if you are, for instanc=
e, a fund that invests money for a religious group, you might tell the mana=
ger=C2=A0to avoid certain sorts of sin stocks. You might chat periodically =
with the manager about what they=E2=80=99re up to, and you might give them =
some input, without quite =E2=80=9Cexercising investment discretion=E2=80=
=9D over the account. The manager=C2=A0makes the investing decisions, but w=
ith your preferences in mind.
You could push this further. Hire an =E2=80=9Cinvestment manager=E2=80=9D t=
o buy and sell stocks for you, but just tell them exactly what to buy and s=
ell. They=E2=80=99re not=C2=A0really=C2=A0in the business of making the inv=
estment decisions; they=E2=80=99re just in the business of sitting between =
you and the public Form 13F requirement. This way you get exactly the stock=
s you want, and presumably a fake investment manager is=C2=A0cheaper=C2=A0t=
han a real one.
This is an imperfect solution, since your fake investment manager presumabl=
y won=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0other=C2=A0clients, so they=C2=A0will file a Form=
 13F that exactly describes your own stock holdings. Your name won=E2=80=99=
t be on it, which is good, but if your holdings are big enough then people =
might be curious. =E2=80=9CWho is this Anonymous Investments LLC that owns =
$30 billion of stock and has one client,=E2=80=9D they might ask. But if yo=
u=E2=80=99re doing this you can hire a=C2=A0bunch=C2=A0of different =E2=80=
=9Cinvestment managers,=E2=80=9D have each of them own some of your stocks,=
 and split up the disclosure=C2=A0into a bunch of anonymous Form 13F filing=
s none of which are big or interesting enough to attract attention.
This is illegal, though you can see how you might feel justified in doing i=
t. =E2=80=9CWhy should random strangers get to know what stocks I own,=E2=
=80=9D you might think. That seems to have been  what the Mormon Church tho=
ught:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today announced charges against Ensi=
gn Peak Advisers Inc., a non-profit entity operated by The Church of Jesus =
Christ of Latter-day Saints to manage the Church=E2=80=99s investments, for=
 failing to file forms that would have disclosed the Church=E2=80=99s equit=
y investments, and for instead filing forms for shell companies that obscur=
ed the Church=E2=80=99s portfolio and misstated Ensign Peak=E2=80=99s contr=
ol over the Church=E2=80=99s investment decisions. The SEC also announced c=
harges against the Church for causing these violations. To settle the charg=
es, Ensign Peak agreed to pay a $4 million penalty and the Church agreed to=
 pay a $1 million penalty.
The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that, from 1997 through 2019, Ensign Peak fai=
led to file Forms 13F, the forms on which investment managers are required =
to disclose the value of certain securities they manage. According to the o=
rder, the Church was concerned that disclosure of its portfolio, which by 2=
018 grew to approximately $32 billion, would lead to negative consequences.=
 To obscure the amount of the Church=E2=80=99s portfolio, and with the Chur=
ch=E2=80=99s knowledge and approval, Ensign Peak created thirteen shell LLC=
s, ostensibly with locations throughout the U.S., and filed Forms 13F in th=
e names of these LLCs rather than in Ensign Peak=E2=80=99s name. The order =
finds that Ensign Peak maintained investment discretion over all relevant s=
ecurities, that it controlled the shell companies, and that it directed nom=
inee =E2=80=9Cbusiness managers,=E2=80=9D most of whom were employed by the=
 Church, to sign the Commission filings. The shell LLCs=E2=80=99 Forms 13F =
misstated, among other things, that the LLCs had sole investment and voting=
 discretion over the securities. In reality, the SEC=E2=80=99s order finds,=
 Ensign Peak retained control over all investment and voting decisions.

=E2=80=9CThe Church was concerned that disclosure of the assets in the name=
 of Ensign Peak, a known Church affiliate, would lead to negative consequen=
ces in light of the size of the Church=E2=80=99s portfolio,=E2=80=9D  says =
the complaint, and you can see their point. The effect of the 13F rules her=
e is mostly to make public that the church has a lot of money. But the rule=
s are the rules, and setting up 13 shell LLCs to pretend to manage your mon=
ey for you doesn=E2=80=99t really work to get around them.

