       =20
  [1] In fact AMC sold about 241.6 million shares for about $1.6 billion in=
 2021, for an average price of about $6.67, not much higher than today=E2=
=80=99s share price (and today=E2=80=99s price is after the 2-for-1-ish pse=
udo-stock-split caused by the APEs). But that average price is low because =
it was selling a lot in desperation in early 2021, and had  only a few mill=
ion shares left to sell by June 2021 when its stock was trading above $60 o=
n meme energy. If shareholders had approved more shares *then*, as AMC=E2=
=80=99s executives wanted, it could have hit that bid.


  [2] A complicating factor here is that *not* voting to convert them, and =
just letting AMC issue more APEs, is also dilutive, since it is effectively=
 selling common-stock-like securities at a huge discount to the price of th=
e common stock.


  [3] The law =E2=80=94 DGCL section 242(b) =E2=80=94 also says that shareh=
olders get to vote as a class =E2=80=9Cif the amendment would increase or d=
ecrease the aggregate number of authorized shares of such class,=E2=80=9D b=
ut a later sentence says that =E2=80=9CThe number of authorized shares of a=
ny such class or classes of stock may be increased or decreased (but not be=
low the number of shares thereof then outstanding) by the affirmative vote =
of the holders of a majority of the stock of the corporation entitled to vo=
te irrespective of this subsection, if so provided in the original certific=
ate of incorporation,=E2=80=9D and AMC=E2=80=99s charter does opt out of th=
at requirement. So the shareholders here can=E2=80=99t rely on *that* rule,=
 but there is no exception for reducing the rights and powers of the class.


  [4] Even the shareholder plaintiffs here  kind of agree: =E2=80=9CThe Boa=
rd=E2=80=99s decision to sell the authorized Class A common shares was enor=
mously profitable=E2=80=94raising over $1.8 billion in 2021. With this enor=
mous influx of cash, the Company=E2=80=99s Board paid down some of its debt=
s, obtained an increase in the Company=E2=80=99s credit rating, and embarke=
d on an investment spree, greatly diversifying the Company=E2=80=99s invest=
ments.=E2=80=9D


  [5] The reason is that the law says that the lead plaintiff =E2=80=94 who=
 does stuff like choose the lawyers and negotiate their fee =E2=80=94 has t=
o be the shareholder who is =E2=80=9Cmost capable of adequately representin=
g the interests of class members=E2=80=9D and who =E2=80=9Chas the largest =
financial interest=E2=80=9D in the case, which tends to mean that it has to=
 be a biggish professional institution, but the biggest asset managers most=
ly don=E2=80=99t want to anger companies by leading lawsuits against them.


  [6] Or, 99.9% of the shares are the ones that vote =E2=80=94 common share=
s that don=E2=80=99t vote still count as votes against the proposal, but th=
ey are swamped by the 1,000-vote preferred.


  [7] More specifically,  Rule 13f-1 provides that =E2=80=9CEvery instituti=
onal investment manager which exercises investment discretion with respect =
to accounts holding section 13(f) securities =E2=80=A6 having an aggregate =
fair market value on the last trading day of any month of any calendar year=
 of at least $100,000,000 shall file a report on Form 13F =E2=80=A6 within =
45 days after the last day of such calendar year and within 45 days after t=
he last day of each of the first three calendar quarters of the subsequent =
calendar year.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CSection 13(f) securities=E2=80=9D means ba=
sically publicly traded stocks. =E2=80=9C Institutional investment manager=
=E2=80=9D  means basically anyone other than an individual person trading t=
heir own personal account. So rich individuals trading their own accounts a=
re not subject to the rule.


  [8] The  rules say: =E2=80=9CA person exercises =E2=80=98investment discr=
etion=E2=80=99 with respect to an account if, directly or indirectly, such =
person (A) is authorized to determine what securities or other property sha=
ll be purchased or sold by or for the account, (B) makes decisions as to wh=
at securities or other property shall be purchased or sold by or for the ac=
count even though some other person may have responsibility for such invest=
ment decisions, or (C) otherwise exercises such influence with respect to t=
he purchase and sale of securities or other property by or for the account =
as the Commission, by rule, determines, in the public interest or for the p=
rotection of investors, should be subject to the operation of the provision=
s of this chapter and the rules and regulations thereunder.=E2=80=9D


  [9] Random fact: I am currently reading Jack Schwager=E2=80=99s Hedge Fun=
d Market Wizards, which features Dalio and notes that, when he was intervie=
wed for the book in 2011, he had recently transitioned from running Bridgew=
ater to serving as its =E2=80=9Cmentor.=E2=80=9D This weekend=E2=80=99s Tim=
es article describes a 2022 negotiation between Dalio and Bridgewater in wh=
ich Dalio agreed that he would =E2=80=9Csurrender his titles, take on a new=
 role as =E2=80=98mentor to the C.I.O.s and investment committee,=E2=80=99 =
and remain a member of the hedge fund=E2=80=99s board.=E2=80=9D Ray Dalio i=
s in a perpetual state of having just agreed to resign as Bridgewater=E2=80=
=99s CIO to become its mentor.


