</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have previously <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDEvYW1jLWhhcy1zb21lLWNsZXZlci1hcGVzP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB8b5fbb14" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> expressed my fondness</a>=C2=A0for AMC =
Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s APEs=C2=A0scheme. AMC was a big meme =
stock and had=C2=A0a lot of investors who wanted to buy its stock; it also =
needed a lot of money and was happy to sell stock to them. But its corporat=
e charter only allowed it to issue about 524 million common shares, and AMC=
 was running out of stock to sell. It asked its shareholders to authorize m=
ore shares but =E2=80=94=C2=A0well, they didn=E2=80=99t exactly say no. Wha=
t happened is that AMC withdrew the request for more shares because it coul=
dn=E2=80=99t get enough votes, and it couldn=E2=80=99t get enough votes=C2=
=A0<em>in part=C2=A0</em>because its existing shareholders were worried abo=
ut dilution, but also in (probably larger) part because AMC=E2=80=99s overw=
helmingly retail investor base simply doesn=E2=80=99t vote. Retail sharehol=
ders tend not to vote much on anything; they are hard to reach, and voting =
your shares is confusing and pointless enough that ordinary retail investor=
s rarely do it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But AMC needed a majority of all of its shares=
 to vote to authorize new shares; not voting is equivalent to voting no. So=
 AMC had people who wanted to buy stock, it wanted to sell them stock, and =
it (probably) thought that its shareholders wanted it to issue more stock =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it couldn=E2=80=99t reach those shareholders to get them=
 to vote to approve more stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So AMC came up with a clever trick, the APEs, =
AMC Preferred Equity Units. It created a new class of preferred stock; each=
 preferred share has the economic rights of 100 shares of common stock, get=
s 100 votes and votes together with the common stock on everything. Then it=
 gave its shareholders 1/100th of a preferred share =E2=80=94=C2=A0an APE =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0for each common share, creating sort of a stock split. Then =
it started selling more APEs to raise cash, and sold a big block of APEs to=
 a hedge fund called Antara Capital. And now it is=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhl=
LXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6931b81" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> asking its shareholders</a> =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0APE holders and common shareholders, all voting together =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to approve a charter amendment to authorize new shares, do a re=
verse share split and convert the APEs into common shares. This vote should=
 succeed, because:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are now many more APEs than com=
mon shares, and the APE holders have an incentive to vote yes. (APEs trade =
at a big discount to common shares, and if the APEs are converted that disc=
ount will naturally close.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">APEs a=
re more likely to be held by professional arbitrageurs, not retail investor=
s, so they are more likely to vote.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">A big block of APEs is held by Antara, which has signed an agreement to v=
ote its shares in favor of the amendment.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">The preferred shares underlying the APEs are held by a depositary, =
Computershare Trust Co., which has agreed to vote=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of=
 the preferred shares in proportion to how any voting APEs vote. So if 20% =
of the APEs vote yes, 5% vote no, and 75% don=E2=80=99t vote at all, Comput=
ershare will vote 80% of the preferred stock for yes, which will be enough =
to pass the amendments even if all of the common stock doesn=E2=80=99t vote=
 (or votes no).</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC=E2=80=99s problem was that its retail inve=
stors don=E2=80=99t vote, and it came up with a solution. I like it!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not everyone does. <em>Before=C2=A0</em>the AP=
Es, it probably made sense for AMC=E2=80=99s common shareholders to vote to=
 authorize more shares: AMC needed money, and if it could sell shares at hi=
gh prices to new investors, that was good for existing shareholders. (If yo=
u are selling stock at prices higher than fundamental value, that=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0<em>accretive</em>, not dilutive.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>) A rational AMC shareholder, pre-APEs, probably <em>should</em> have w=
anted to authorize more shares, even if the shareholders=C2=A0did not bothe=
r to=C2=A0<em>vote=C2=A0</em>to make that happen.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now that the APEs=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>o=
utstanding, the common shareholders might rationally not want to convert th=
em into common stock. The APEs closed on Friday at $2.40 per APE; the commo=
n stock closed at $5.24. When the APEs convert into common, those prices wi=
ll converge. It=E2=80=99s not entirely clear if the final price should be c=
loser to $2.40 or $5.24, but it=E2=80=99s plausible that it would be somewh=
ere in the middle, meaning that voting for the conversion would <em>reduce=
=C2=A0</em>the value of the common stock. If you are a common shareholder, =
converting all the APEs into common stock definitely=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>=
dilutive, and you might not like it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You might vote against authorizing new shares. That doesn=E2=80=
=99t matter very much: The APEs have a majority of the voting power and are=
 very incentivized to vote for their own conversion. But you might be mad.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might sue.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5p=
by9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JFZXNlSWdZYUZQYy92MA/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB0c2921e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">Here is a lawsuit</a> against AMC that was f=
iled in Delaware Chancery Court yesterday:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This Action challenges a course of complex and=
 disloyal corporate engineering by the Defendants=E2=80=94described by AMC=
=E2=80=99s Chief Executive Officer and Chairman, Defendant Adam M. Aron (=
=E2=80=9CAron=E2=80=9D) as an exercise in =E2=80=9C3-D chess=E2=80=9D=E2=80=
=94 devised to achieve a simple aim: eviscerating the voting power of AMC=
=E2=80=99s Class A stockholders in order to force through approval of a pro=
posed dilutive share count increase that those stockholders repeatedly had =
rebuffed and were not willing to support at the corporate ballot box. ...</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seizing on increases in AMC=E2=80=99s stock pr=
ice driven by retail investors, AMC sold nearly all of the Company=E2=80=99=
s remaining authorized shares of Class A common stock to raise capital. The=
reafter, AMC proposed on multiple occasions to amend the Company=E2=80=99s =
certificate of incorporation to authorize the issuance of additional shares=
 of Class A common stock=E2=80=94but those proposals were rebuffed repeated=
ly by the Company=E2=80=99s existing Class A common stockholders, who twice=
 forced the withdrawal of such proposals.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response, AMC embarked on a course of compl=
ex corporate engineering for the plain and obvious purpose of circumventing=
 the will of the Company=E2=80=99s existing stockholders and securing a dil=
utive increase in the number of authorized Class A shares over their unambi=
guous opposition. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With outstanding APEs outnumbering the Class A=
 common shares by nearly 2 to 1 and the Depositary Voting Requirement super=
charging the APEs=E2=80=99 voting power as a class vis-=C3=A0-vis AMC=E2=80=
=99s Class A stockholders, AMC is poised to finally force through the Class=
 A share count increase that was opposed repeatedly by Class A stockholders=
 before AMC and the Board took steps to reconstitute their electorate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC and the Board presumably believe their gam=
e of =E2=80=9C3-D chess=E2=80=9D against the Class A stockholders is approa=
ching checkmate. But, as detailed herein, the vote cannot be allowed to pro=
ceed as planned. In their zeal to circumvent the will of the Class A stockh=
olders, Defendants have breached their fiduciary duties and violated the [D=
elaware General Corporation=C2=A0Law].</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two main arguments. One is sort of a=
 technical one: <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30=
618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWxjb2RlLmRlbGF3YXJlLmdvdi90aXRsZTgvYzAwMS9zYzA4L=
2luZGV4Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8def53a5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Delaware law</a> =
says that the common shareholders have to get to vote on any charter amendm=
ent that would =E2=80=9Calter or change the powers, preferences, or special=
 rights of the shares of such class so as to affect them adversely,=E2=80=
=9D and the shareholders here argue that=C2=A0<em>the issuance of the APEs=
=C2=A0</em>reduced their rights and so should have been put to a shareholde=
r vote.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> The APEs are what is called =E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred stock,=E2=
=80=9D meaning that AMC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy=
9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTEzMDkyMDAxL2ExMy0yNjk1N18xZXgzZDEua=
HRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB834e96f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">corporate charter</a>=C2=A0a=
llows the board of directors to create and issue new preferred stock with w=
hatever terms they like, but the argument here is that creating the APEs re=
duced the rights of the common and so separately violated the law:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the time the Board created the Preferred Sh=
ares, AMC had only one class of authorized stock with voting rights, its Cl=
ass A common stock. The right to vote on matters requiring stockholder appr=
oval was not shared with any other class. Thus, the right to vote was a spe=
cial characteristic of the common stock in the capital structure of AMC.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, the sole or primary purpose of t=
he Preferred Stock=E2=80=99s creation and issuance was to eviscerate the vo=
ting power of the Company=E2=80=99s Class A=C2=A0stockholders and effective=
ly fashion a new electorate that, unlike the pre-existing stockholder base,=
 would not rebuff the Board=E2=80=99s proposals to issue additional common =
stock. That is, before the creation of the Preferred Stock, AMC=E2=80=99s C=
lass A stockholders had the power and right to reject a specific proposal d=
esired by the Board. This power and right conflicted with the desires of th=
e Board, so the Board created and issued the Preferred Stock for the purpos=
e of removing that power and right from the Company=E2=80=99s Class A stock=
holders.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not really convinced =E2=80=94=C2=A0if th=
is is right, then that means that boards can never issue=C2=A0voting prefer=
red stock without shareholder approval, which might make sense but would co=
me as=C2=A0a surprise =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you can see the appeal of it. It=
=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>strange to think that=C2=A0boards could issue new sh=
ares with unlimited voting power without shareholder approval.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other argument is that the board violated =
its fiduciary duty to shareholders: Even if the technical mechanics of the =
APEs all work, AMC created the APEs to get around its shareholders=E2=80=99=
 preferences, which seems icky and disloyal. From the complaint:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Director Defendants approved t=
he creation and sale of the Preferred Stock, imposed the Depositary Voting =
Requirement, and arranged for the impending vote on the Proposals all for t=
he purpose of circumventing the will of the Company=E2=80=99s existing stoc=
kholders, who previously had rejected proposals by the Board to increase th=
e total number of authorized shares of Class A common stock=E2=80=94essenti=
ally creating a new electorate=C2=A0and new voting rules, simply because th=
ey did not have the votes to get what they wanted. All of these steps were =
taken for the very purpose of reversing the likely outcome of Defendants=E2=
=80=99 desired vote to increase the authorized number of Class A shares. Th=
is course of conduct constituted a breach of fiduciary duty.</p></blockquot=
e>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here again I think I sympathize with the board=
. It=E2=80=99s their job to run the company. In the exercise of their=C2=A0=
fiduciary duty, thinking about what is best for the company and its shareho=
lders, they figured the company would be better off issuing more stock. The=
ir reasoning for that =E2=80=94 that the company=C2=A0needed money and=C2=
=A0people <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705=
.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDY=
tMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRk=
YmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjIxJ=
nV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCb6931b81" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 wanted to buy the stock at $60</a>! =E2=80=94=C2=A0was, I think,=C2=A0impe=
ccable.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But they couldn=E2=80=99t do it, because they couldn=E2=80=99t ge=
t shareholder approval, in part because shareholders disagreed with them bu=
t in large part because the shareholders simply didn=E2=80=99t vote. The co=
mpany had a problem, its shareholders could not get their act together to s=
olve it, so the board solved it for them. That=E2=80=99s what the board is =
supposed to do, and Delaware courts do tend to be pretty sympathetic to boa=
rds of directors who make what they think is the right decision for their c=
ompany even if the shareholders don=E2=80=99t like it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But they are less sympathetic to boards who tr=
y to take voting rights away from shareholders, and there is something abou=
t the APEs that feels like cheating. So I don=E2=80=99t know what will happ=
en. The special meeting to authorize new shares and convert the APEs into c=
ommon is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.=
287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYt=
MDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjIxJn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cDb6931b81" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 scheduled for March 14</a>; the complaining shareholders=C2=A0have <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JXWmhXTVhYa1ZI=
VS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf2b19c9b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">asked to postpone it</a>=
 for 60 days while they argue to block it in court.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other point here. Shareholder class action=
 lawsuits like this are now usually filed by institutional investors, often=
 municipal retirement funds.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The lead plaintiff here =E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholder who brough=
t the lawsuit =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the=C2=A0Allegheny County Employees=E2=80=
=99 Retirement System, a pretty normal shareholder class-action plaintiff, =
yet one who is somehow unrepresentative of AMC=E2=80=99s meme-stock shareho=
lders. Really you want a pseudonymous individual Reddit poster to lead the =
lawsuit.</p>
