<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There seems to have been a wave of companies r=
ecently that are using blank-check preferred stock to get around a lack of =
enthusiasm for shareholder voting. AMC is the highest-profile example, but =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMTYvdGhlL=
XNlYy1jb21lcy1mb3ItY3J5cHRvLWN1c3RvZHk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYm=
dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjIxJnV=
0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e30c257" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  we talked last week about Soligenix Inc.</a>, which had a different appro=
ach: It gave all shareholders a dividend of a special preferred stock that =
gave them an extra 1,000 votes per common share, but the preferred automati=
cally disappears (1) right before the shareholder vote, if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t vote, or (2) right after the shareholder vote, if it does vote. So at =
the time of the vote, the only shares that are outstanding are the ones tha=
t vote,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> so you never face the problem where a majority of the shareholders=C2=
=A0<em>who actually vote </em>vote for the thing you want, but most shareho=
lders don=E2=80=99t vote at all so it doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0pass.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, I think, a bit weirder than the AMC a=
pproach, but also less aggressive; AMC=E2=80=99s approach involved placing =
big chunks of new stock with sympathetic holders, while this one is just so=
rt of an accounting trick. Anyway it=E2=80=99s now a trend; Regional Health=
 Properties <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/306187=
05.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwMDQ3MjQvM=
DAwMTQ5MzE1MjIzMDA1NDc5L2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB280c59aa" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> did one last Friday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Regional Health Properties, Inc. =E2=80=A6 ann=
ounced today that its Board of Directors declared a dividend of one one-tho=
usandth (1/1,000th) of a share of the Company=E2=80=99s newly-designated Se=
ries E Redeemable Preferred Shares, no par value per share (the =E2=80=9CSe=
ries E Preferred Stock=E2=80=9D), for each outstanding share of the Company=
=E2=80=99s common stock (=E2=80=9CCommon Stock=E2=80=9D), payable on Februa=
ry 28, 2023 to shareholders of record as of 5:00 p.m. Eastern Time on Febru=
ary 27, 2023. The outstanding shares of Series E Preferred Stock will vote =
together with the outstanding shares of Common Stock, as a single class, ex=
clusively with respect to (a) any proposal submitted to holders of Common S=
tock to amend the Company=E2=80=99s Amended and Restated Articles of Incorp=
oration to (i) make certain changes to the terms of the Company=E2=80=99s 1=
0.875% Series A Cumulative Redeemable Preferred Shares and (ii) temporarily=
 increase the authorized number of shares of the Company (including the aut=
horized shares of the Company=E2=80=99s preferred stock) (the =E2=80=9CChar=
ter Amendment Proposal=E2=80=9D) .... Subject to certain limitations, each =
outstanding share of Series E Preferred Stock will have 1,000,000 votes per=
 share (or 1,000 votes per one one-thousandth of a share of Series E Prefer=
red Stock).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All shares of Series E Preferred Stock that ar=
e not present in person or by proxy at any meeting of shareholders held to =
vote on the above-described proposals as of immediately prior to the openin=
g of the polls on the Charter Amendment Proposal at such meeting will autom=
atically be redeemed by the Company. Any outstanding shares of Series E Pre=
ferred Stock that have not been so redeemed will be redeemed if such redemp=
tion is ordered by the Company=E2=80=99s Board of Directors or automaticall=
y upon the approval by the Company=E2=80=99s shareholders of the Charter Am=
endment Proposal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the one hand it seems like a good solution.=
 On the other hand, the law says that this sort of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0her=
e, approving the issuance of new shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0requires the approva=
l of a majority of the outstanding=C2=A0shares, not just a majority of the =
shares that vote. If you can magically get around that requirement with thi=
s sort of accounting gimmick, then it=E2=80=99s not much of a requirement.<=
/p>
