<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rule in the US is roughly=C2=A0that if you=
 are an institution =E2=80=94=C2=A0a pension fund, an endowment, an investm=
ent firm, a bank, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you own more than $100 million wo=
rth of stocks, you have to disclose your stock holdings every quarter.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You file <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9wZGYvZm9ybTEzZi5wZGY/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB065f2c04" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">Form 13F</a> with the US Securities and Ex=
change Commission, and it is publicly available and everyone can see what s=
tocks you own.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you don=E2=80=99t like this, there are reas=
onably standard solutions. The rule is actually that you have to file Form =
13F if you =E2=80=9Cexercise investment discretion=E2=80=9D over your stock=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning basically that you decide what stocks to buy and s=
ell<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0so the trick is not to do that. If you have $1 bil=
lion to invest in the stock market, you go to a big institutional investmen=
t manager and say =E2=80=9Chi, here=E2=80=99s $1 billion, please buy some s=
tocks for me.=E2=80=9D You agree on some investment criteria =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the mandate for your investment =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you pay the manager s=
ome fees, and the manager buys the stocks for you. This saves you all sorts=
 of aggravation =E2=80=94=C2=A0picking the stocks, doing the trading, setti=
ng up custody arrangements, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it also probably saves =
you from filing a Form 13F, if that=E2=80=99s your goal. Instead, the inves=
tment management firm files a Form 13F showing all of the stocks that it ow=
ns =E2=80=94=C2=A0that it =E2=80=9Cexercises investment discretion=E2=80=9D=
 over =E2=80=94=C2=A0for its various clients, including you. You are just a=
n anonymous client; your data is aggregated with the rest of the clients.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Presumably if you=E2=80=99re a big enough acco=
unt, and interested enough in the markets, you might end up doing some kibb=
itzing about what your investment manager is buying. The manager=E2=80=99s =
mandate for your account might be narrow and customized for=C2=A0your inter=
ests; if you are, for instance, a fund that invests money for a religious g=
roup, you might tell the manager=C2=A0to avoid certain sorts of sin stocks.=
 You might chat periodically with the manager about what they=E2=80=99re up=
 to, and you might give them some input, without quite =E2=80=9Cexercising =
investment discretion=E2=80=9D over the account. The manager=C2=A0makes the=
 investing decisions, but with your preferences in mind.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could push this further. Hire an =E2=80=9C=
investment manager=E2=80=9D to buy and sell stocks for you, but just tell t=
hem exactly what to buy and sell. They=E2=80=99re not=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0=
</em>in the business of making the investment decisions; they=E2=80=99re ju=
st in the business of sitting between you and the public Form 13F requireme=
nt. This way you get exactly the stocks you want, and presumably a fake inv=
estment manager is=C2=A0<em>cheaper=C2=A0</em>than a real one.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is an imperfect solution, since your fake=
 investment manager presumably won=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>=
clients, so they=C2=A0will file a Form 13F that exactly describes your own =
stock holdings. Your name won=E2=80=99t be on it, which is good, but if you=
r holdings are big enough then people might be curious. =E2=80=9CWho is thi=
s Anonymous Investments LLC that owns $30 billion of stock and has one clie=
nt,=E2=80=9D they might ask. But if you=E2=80=99re doing this you can hire =
a=C2=A0<em>bunch=C2=A0</em>of different =E2=80=9Cinvestment managers,=E2=80=
=9D have each of them own some of your stocks, and split up the disclosure=
=C2=A0into a bunch of anonymous Form 13F filings none of which are big or i=
nteresting enough to attract attention.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is illegal, though you can see how you mi=
ght feel justified in doing it. =E2=80=9CWhy should random strangers get to=
 know what stocks I own,=E2=80=9D you might think. That seems to have been =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30618705.287441/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0zNQ/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBc253557a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> what the Mormon Church thought</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today a=
nnounced charges against Ensign Peak Advisers Inc., a non-profit entity ope=
rated by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints to manage the Chur=
ch=E2=80=99s investments, for failing to file forms that would have disclos=
ed the Church=E2=80=99s equity investments, and for instead filing forms fo=
r shell companies that obscured the Church=E2=80=99s portfolio and misstate=
d Ensign Peak=E2=80=99s control over the Church=E2=80=99s investment decisi=
ons. The SEC also announced charges against the Church for causing these vi=
olations. To settle the charges, Ensign Peak agreed to pay a $4 million pen=
alty and the Church agreed to pay a $1 million penalty.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that, from 1997 =
through 2019, Ensign Peak failed to file Forms 13F, the forms on which inve=
stment managers are required to disclose the value of certain securities th=
ey manage. According to the order, the Church was concerned that disclosure=
 of its portfolio, which by 2018 grew to approximately $32 billion, would l=
ead to negative consequences. To obscure the amount of the Church=E2=80=99s=
 portfolio, and with the Church=E2=80=99s knowledge and approval, Ensign Pe=
ak created thirteen shell LLCs, ostensibly with locations throughout the U.=
S., and filed Forms 13F in the names of these LLCs rather than in Ensign Pe=
ak=E2=80=99s name. The order finds that Ensign Peak maintained investment d=
iscretion over all relevant securities, that it controlled the shell compan=
ies, and that it directed nominee =E2=80=9Cbusiness managers,=E2=80=9D most=
 of whom were employed by the Church, to sign the Commission filings. The s=
hell LLCs=E2=80=99 Forms 13F misstated, among other things, that the LLCs h=
ad sole investment and voting discretion over the securities. In reality, t=
he SEC=E2=80=99s order finds, Ensign Peak retained control over all investm=
ent and voting decisions.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe Church was concerned that disclos=
ure of the assets in the name of Ensign Peak, a known Church affiliate, wou=
ld lead to negative consequences in light of the size of the Church=E2=80=
=99s portfolio,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/30618705.287441/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIw=
MjMvMzQtOTY5NTEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBab9ae1df" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says the c=
omplaint</a>, and you can see their point. The effect of the 13F rules here=
 is mostly to make public that the church has a lot of money. But the rules=
 are the rules, and setting up 13 shell LLCs to pretend to manage your mone=
y for you doesn=E2=80=99t really work to get around them.</p>
