traded real estate companies or tech stocks falls by 50%, you might say =E2=
=80=9Chuh, shame about all those public companies having problems, but=C2=
=A0<em>our=C2=A0</em>portfolio is actually=C2=A0<em>up=C2=A0</em>1% this ye=
ar.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One interpretation of this is that the=C2=A0<e=
m>fundamental value </em>of your sector=C2=A0really did fall by 50%, and th=
e public market price reflects the best possible consensus of that fact, an=
d you are just able to ignore that because there is no publicly traded mark=
 for your portfolio. Another, opposite interpretation is that the fundament=
al value hasn=E2=80=99t changed, but the public market panicked for reasons=
 of its own, and you =E2=80=94=C2=A0with your patient approach and absence =
of a trading price =E2=80=94=C2=A0can just consider fundamental value and i=
gnore meaningless volatility.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the latter case, private investors should w=
ant to buy public assets (and make them private) when the public market col=
lapses, and sell private assets (to make them public) when the public marke=
t rallies. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/306=
